messageBody:
here are three alternate full forms provided in Quikscript, and eight
alternate half forms for ease of running on and connecting with the
next letter.

The three alternate full forms are the second in each pair of QS keys
listed below. (The first line answers the question.)

For Std English thee, the QS keys are H and K (alternate).
For Std English n, the QS keys are n and G (alternate).
For Std English a (unstressed as in ado), the QS keys are a and u
(alternate).

The eight alternate half forms as follows:

For Std English p, the QS keys are p (full) and ] (half)
For Std English t, the QS keys are t (full) and D (half)
For Std English d, the QS keys are d (full) and B (half)
For Std English z, the QS keys are z (full) and L (half)

For Std English w, the QS keys are w (full) and @ (half)
For Std English h, the QS keys are h (full) and \ (half)
For Std English wh, the QS keys are ` (full) and ~ (half)
For Std English y, the QS keys are j (full) and ^ (half)

Cossy

--- In Read_Alphabet@yahoogroups.com, "Joe" <allegrox_2000@y...> wrote:
>
> I'm not sure what this is. My guess is that it's either a form of
\H\ with the end
> curled up to connect to the next letter or it's a ligature of \H@\
(= \Ht\. It's not a
> common cluster, though.
>
> --- In Read_Alphabet@yahoogroups.com, "BP Jonsson" <bpj@m...> wrote:
> >
> > What does the character mapped to the capital |K| key
> > in the fonts mean? I guess it is _shw_ or _sht_, but
> > I can't find it in the manual...
> >
